1. Rates of Reaction
•	Average Rate: The change in a measurable quantity (like mass or volume) divided by the time taken for that change to occur.
•	Catalyst: A substance that increases the rate of a chemical reaction without being used up itself.
•	Collision Theory: The theory that for a reaction to occur, particles must collide with enough energy (activation energy) and in the correct orientation.
•	End-point: The moment a reaction is finished (often shown on a graph when the curve flattens out). 
 
2. Atomic Structure
•	Atom: The smallest particle of an element that can exist.
•	Proton: A positively charged particle found in the nucleus (mass = 1 amu).
•	Neutron: A neutral particle found in the nucleus (mass = 1 amu).
•	Electron: A negatively charged particle found in energy levels orbiting the nucleus (mass is negligible).
•	Atomic Number: The number of protons in the nucleus of an atom.
•	Mass Number: The total number of protons and neutrons in the nucleus.
•	Isotopes: Atoms of the same element with the same number of protons(same atomic number) but a different number of neutrons (different mass numbers).
•	Nuclide Notation: A way of writing an atom showing its mass number (top) and atomic number (bottom) next to the element symbol.
•	Ion: An atom (or group of atoms) that has gained or lost electrons, resulting in a positive or negative charge. 
 
3. Bonding and Structure
•	Periodic Table: A table of elements arranged by increasing atomic number.
•	Group: A vertical column in the periodic table; elements in the same group have the same number of outer electrons and similar chemical properties.
•	Period: A horizontal row in the periodic table.
•	Covalent Bond: A bond formed between non-metal atoms by the sharing of a pair of electrons.
•	Diatomic: A molecule consisting of only two atoms (e.g.,  H2, N2 , CO, HCl)
•	Covalent Molecular: Substances with strong covalent bonds inside molecules but weak forces between molecules; they have low melting/boiling points and do not conduct electricity.
•	Covalent Network: A giant structure of atoms held together by strong covalent bonds; they have very high melting points and do not conduct electricity (except graphite).
•	Ionic Bond: The strong electrostatic attraction between positive and negative ions.
•	Ionic Lattice: A repeating 3D structure of oppositely charged ions; they have high melting points and conduct electricity only when molten or in solution.
•	Valency: The combining power of an element or group of atoms, related to the number of electrons an atom needs to gain or lose to reach a stable shell. 
 
4. Formulae and Reacting Quantities
•	Chemical Formula: Represents the ratio of atoms or ions in a substance.
•	Balanced Equation: An equation where the number of each type of atom is the same on both the reactant and product sides.
•	Mole: The unit used to measure the amount of a substance.
•	Gram Formula Mass (GFM): The mass of one mole of a substance in grams.
•	State Symbols: Letters used in equations to show the state of matter: (s) solid, (l) liquid, (g) gas, (aq) aqueous (dissolved in water).
•	Concentration: The amount of solute (in moles) dissolved in a given volume of solvent (usually in mol l-1). 
 




5. Acids and Bases
•	Acid: A substance with a pH less than 7. It contains a higher concentration of H+ ions than OH- ions.
•	Alkali: A soluble base with a pH greater than 7. It contains a higher concentration of OH- ions than H+ ions.
•	Neutral Solution: A solution with a pH of 7; the concentration of H+ ions equals the concentration of OH- ions.
•	Neutralisation: A reaction where an acid reacts with a base (alkali, metal oxide, metal hydroxide, or metal carbonate) to form salt and water.
•	Spectator Ions: Ions that are present during a reaction but do not take part in the actual chemical change.
•	Titration: A technique used to determine the exact volume of acid/alkali required to reach the end-point of a neutralisation reaction.
•	Indicator: A substance that changes colour to show the end-point of a titration. 
Unit 2
Homologous Series & Hydrocarbons
•	Homologous Series: A family of compounds with the same general formula, similar chemical properties, and a trend in physical properties.
•	Hydrocarbon: A compound containing only carbon and hydrogen atoms.
•	Saturated: Compounds containing only carbon-carbon single bonds.
•	Unsaturated: Compounds containing at least one carbon-carbon double bond (C=C).
•	Alkanes: A saturated homologous series with the general formula CnH2n+2.
•	Alkenes: An unsaturated homologous series with the general formula CnH2n.
•	Cycloalkanes: A saturated, ring-shaped homologous series with the general formula CnH2n
•	Isomers: Compounds with the same molecular formula but different structural formulae.
•	Bromine Water Test: Used to distinguish between saturated and unsaturated compounds. Unsaturated compounds (alkenes) quickly turn bromine water from orange/brown to colourless.
•	Addition Reaction: A reaction where a molecule (e.g., hydrogen, water, or bromine) adds across the double bond of an unsaturated compound, breaking the double bond.
o	Hydrogenation: Addition of hydrogen.
o	Hydration: Addition of water. 
 
2. Everyday Consumer Products
•	Alcohol: A homologous series containing a hydroxyl group (-OH) General formula: CnH2n+1OH.
•	Carboxylic Acid: A homologous series containing a carboxyl group (COOH). General formula: CnH2n+1COOH.
 
3. Energy from Fuels
•	Combustion: The burning of a substance in oxygen. It is an exothermic reaction.
•	Exothermic Reaction: A reaction that releases energy to the surroundings (temperature of surroundings increases).
•	Endothermic Reaction: A reaction that absorbs energy from the surroundings (temperature of surroundings decreases).
•	Fuel: A substance that burns to release energy.
Unit 3 
1. Metals
•	Metallic Bonding: The electrostatic attraction between positively charged metal ions and delocalised electrons.
•	Delocalised Electrons: Electrons that are not bound to a specific atom and are free to move throughout the metallic structure (which is why metals conduct electricity).
•	Reactivity Series: A list of metals arranged in order of how vigorously they react with substances like oxygen, water, or acids.
•	Redox Reaction: A reaction where both reduction (gain of electrons) and oxidation (loss of electrons) occur simultaneously.
•	Reduction: The gain of electrons (e-). In metal extraction, metal ions are reduced to metal atoms. Copy equation p 10
•	Oxidation: The loss of electrons (e-). Reverse equation p10
•	Ion-Electron Equation: An equation showing the oxidation or reduction process, including the movement of electrons.
•	Ore: A naturally occurring rock from which a metal can be extracted.
•	Electrolyte: An ionic solution that conducts electricity.
•	Electrochemical Cell: A setup that produces electricity using two different metals and an electrolyte.
•	Ion Bridge (Salt Bridge): A connection between two half-cells that allows ions to flow and completes the electrical circuit. 
•	Electrolysis: Breaking up an ionic compound using electricity (D.C supply to separate the products)
 
2. Plastics
•	Polymer: A long-chain molecule formed by joining together many small units called monomers.
•	Monomer: A small, unsaturated molecule that reacts to form a polymer.
•	Addition Polymerisation: The reaction where small, unsaturated monomers (usually alkenes) join together to form a polymer, with no other product formed.
 
3. Fertilisers
•	Essential Elements: The three primary nutrients required for plant growth: Nitrogen (N), Phosphorus (P), and Potassium (K).
•	Haber Process: The industrial process used to produce ammonia (NH3) from nitrogen and hydrogen gases using an iron catalyst, temperature of approx. 500 OC, pressure of approx.. 250 atmospheres
•	Ostwald Process: The industrial process used to produce nitric acid from ammonia, water and oxygen using a platinum catalyst
 
4. Nuclear Chemistry
•	Radioisotope: An unstable isotope that emits radiation to become more stable.
•	Alpha Particle: A helium nucleus, with a positive charge. It is heavy, slow-moving, and easily stopped (e.g., by paper).
•	Beta Particle: A high-speed electron ejected from the nucleus. It is lighter and more penetrating than alpha particles (stopped by thin aluminium).
•	Gamma Ray: High-energy electromagnetic radiation. It has no mass or charge and is highly penetrating (requires thick lead or concrete to stop).
•	Half-life: The time taken for the activity (or mass) of a radioisotope to decrease by half. 
 
5. Chemical Analysis
•	Qualitative Analysis: Identifies what substances are present (e.g., flame tests to identify metal ions).
•	Quantitative Analysis: Determines how much of a substance is present (e.g., titrations).
•	Titration: A technique used to accurately measure the volume of a substance required to react with another, often used to determine concentration.
•	Concordant: Titration results that are within 0.2cm3 of each other.
•	Precipitation: The formation of an insoluble solid when two solutions are mixed. 


